    "Syringomyelia is a fluid-filled cavity that expands within the central spinal cord, most often in the cervical region and frequently associated with a Chiari I malformation. The cavity first interrupts the second-order spinothalamic fibers as they decussate in the anterior white commissure, producing bilateral loss of pain and temperature in a cape-like distribution over the shoulders and arms. The dorsal columns (touch, vibration, proprioception) are initially spared, giving the characteristic dissociated sensory loss. Expansion later involves anterior horns and corticospinal tracts.",
