    "A complete mole arises from an empty ovum fertilized by paternal chromosomes, giving a diploid 46,XX karyotype that is entirely paternal, with no fetal parts, a snowstorm uterus, and massively elevated beta-hCG. Because hCG and TSH share an identical alpha subunit (their beta subunits differ), pathologically high hCG can weakly cross-activate the TSH receptor, producing biochemical and occasionally overt hyperthyroidism, most likely when hCG exceeds roughly 400,000 mIU/mL. The thyrotoxicosis resolves after evacuation of the mole. Complete moles also cause hyperemesis, early preeclampsia, and theca lutein cysts, and carry about a 15-20% risk of progression to gestational trophoblastic neoplasia.",
